102 49900
　　從產業革命到二戰結束的短短60年間，世界迭經鉅變。產業革命固然改善了人們的日常生活，卻也同時造成了諸多的社會問題。而兩次世界大戰更給人類帶來了空前的衝擊，其影響至深且遠。面對世局的鉅變，劇院也引發了不少改革的呼聲。從寫實主義起，像自然主義、表達主義、象徵主義、超寫實主義、存在主義、荒謬劇場、殘酷劇場以及敘述劇場等劇場運動紛紛出籠，蔚為西洋戲劇史上的大觀。本課程擬就現代戲劇述其時代背景，論其劇場流派，然後擇取具有代表性的作品，逐一閱讀與討論，使學生在瞭解現代戲劇的背景與流派之餘，更能深入欣賞個別劇作。
Feburury –June, 2015
Teacher: Professor Ching-erh Chang張靜二教授
Telephone No.: (02)23639273
E-mail: chingerh@ntu.edu.tw
Time: Thursday, 10:20-12:10
</>
<c>
102 49920
This course aims to examine a particular line of defining and applying the notion of the sublime. It looks into how artists and philosophers explore our capacity of dealing with mixed feelings while viewing and contemplating art and nature. It is also set in the context of current neuropsychological discourses on mirror neurons that have actually revised certain conventional critical tools such as intentionality and subjectivity. The main focus is on comparing and contrasting different procedures with which we can follow in order to (1) appreciate the subtleties of the sublime and the beautiful; (2) transform our feelings of fear and anxiety into euphoria and knowledge. Other than gathering ideas from the classic texts and scientific papers, students will also devise their own strategies of engaging with strange details or characters found in artistic texts. All in all, this course enlarges on the usefulness of studying philosophical aesthetics in our times.
</>
