<c>
102 50122
English Oral Training II (2) is the second course of the year-long course that aims to enhance students’ formal presentation skills in the English language.  This semester, students will continue to learn how to conduct discussion-based speeches on a wide range of topics.  In addition to a collaborative role play, students will practice 2 in-class speech demonstrations before giving a formal speech at the end of the course.  In addition, students will reflect on their oral learning processes through maintaining a written journal.  Students will also receive constructive feedback from the instructor and the peers as they progress through the course.
</>
<c>
102 50122
Oral training is a course aimed at improving speaking skills, in particular speaking fluency, flexibility and sophistication. OT2 focuses particularly on speaking in public, formal contexts, which requires skills distinct from those used in informal conversation.
Oral presentations are just one way in which these skills can be practised. There are many other contexts that require one type or other of public speaking. In each segment of this course we will begin with a topic (e.g. books you have read), an activity (e.g. a radio programme) or a task (e.g. interview candidates for a job). Preparation activities will be carried out in groups in class, and information may also be gathered out of class, leading to the final presentation (a book fair, a radio programme, a job interview). The preparation phase is at least as important as the presentation itself, as it is here that opportunities arise to improve one’s language and fluency. There may also be oral tests where students speak either in pairs or alone with the teacher on topics previously covered in class.
</>
<c>
102 50122
Course Description
This course has been devised for second-year students in order to increase their competency in oral English. Having completed part one, Argumentation, in this second semester of the course students will be introduced to the history and the rules of debate. Fresh topics will be introduced each week through which students will exercise their debating skills.
</>
<c>
102 50122
一、內容：
This required course for sophomores offers opportunity for further development of English oral skills, correcting pronunciation errors, and listening comprehension practice through (1) creative individual oral presentation projects; (2) poetry recitation; and (3) take-home listening comprehension exercises.
(1) Oral presentation projects: These may include practice in reading an article aloud, telling ghost stories, presenting a ski8ll to the class, giving movie reviews, practicing telephone English, writing and performing skits and plays, producing a mock TV-news program, and writing/translating poetry and reading it to the class.
(2) Poetry: Students will be asked to memorize and recite one poem each week.  Students will receive intensive individual guidance and correction on their pronunciation when they recite the poems.
(3) Take-home listening comprehension exercises: These will include transcriptions, cloze exercises, and answering questions on the content of recorded pieces, e.g. stories, book readings, talk radio, TV and movie dialogs, and pop songs.
二、成績評量方式：
Students who are absent from more than three classes or late to class more than five times without a valid excuse will not receive a grade for this course.  Students are requested to bring a blank 90-minute cassette tape on which will be recorded the poems and some of the listening exercises.
</>
