202 21202
This course introduces the formal and rigorous formalism as well as basic physical concepts and methods of classical mechanics to students. It aims to provide a precise and consistent description of the dynamics of single particles and systems of particles. In the first semester, the course presented a review of relevant mathematics, detailed discussions of advanced topics in Newtonian mechanics, introductions to Lagrangian and Hamiltonian dynamics, and numerous examples (applications).  The topics will be covered in the second semester include:
Central-force motion and orbital dynamics
Dynamics of a system of particles; Collisions
Motion in a non-inertial frame
Dynamics of rigid bodies
Coupled oscillations
Continuous systems; Waves
Special theory of relativity
</>
<c>
202 21302
Recitation classes are for a course with a large class size and are supplemental to the main class. Because there is often a lot of material to cover in the large class, there isn't a lot of time to go over specifics or answer questions. The recitation class gives you the opportunity to address any questions or issues in a smaller classroom environment. Also, quizzes and homework are frequently given
&
/or collected during the recitation class. Every student who registers the recitation course Phys 2018 (力學習題演練下) is required to register the lecture course Phys 2005 (力學下) as well because the recitation is a complement to the lecture. The teaching assistant in charge of the recitation class will guide you through some of the examples and homework problems of the textbook.
</>
