<c>
222 M3080
This is an one-semester, introductory graduate course aiming at beginning graduate students and
advanced undergraduate students. We will provide an extensive and self-contained overview of observational aspects of galaxy formation and evolution, incorporating the latest results. The course is broadly organized into 3 parts: "basic properties and observational techniques", "evolution and environments", and "galaxy formation and baryons in the universe", taught by Drs. Wei-Hao
Wang, Yen-Ting Lin, and Tzu-Ching Chang, respectively. Some basic knowledge of cosmology is preferred, although not required. We will not have exams, although active classroom participation is highly desired; the grading is based on homework and a final report. The final report will be a proposal requesting either telescope time for an observational project or support for conducting theoretical studies. The proposals will be reviewed and graded based on the scientific merit. The lectures will be delivered in English, and both homework and the final report should be written in English.
</>
<c>
222 M6040
The module will introduce the theory of quarks and gluons, QCD.
The pre-QCD parton model and the Bjorken scaling will be discussed.
The concepts of confinement and asymptotic freedom will be covered.
Experimental proof of the existence of quarks and gluons came from
deep inelastic scattering experiments that probed the structure of
the hadrons. These experiments measured in detail the momentum
distributions of quarks and gluons in the proton.
QCD measurements in hadron colliders will also be discussed.
The module will also cover the chiral symmetry breaking of QCD
leading to the appearance of pseudo-Goldstones, the pions.
We will use these ideas to  introduce potential new strong interaction
sectors which can explain the origin of the Higgs boson, the fermion
mass hierarchy problem, and the unification of interactions.
</>
<c>
222 M6050
A pedagogical introduction to string theory.
(1) bosonic strings
(2) superstrings
(3) open strings, unoriented strings
(4) compactifications
(5) string duality and branes
</>
<c>
222 U0330
量子光學為近代原子分子科學提供重要的理論基礎與實驗技術。其探討物質與電磁波在原子與分子尺度下的交互作用所呈現的量子特性及行為，從而研究如何加以控制。本課程將由從基礎的二能級系統出發，介紹密度矩陣及主方程的數學架構、光的量子特性、物質與光的交互作用描述及控制方法的實現，並概述此領域在當代的一些重要課題及概念發展，如：雷射冷卻(laser cooling)、光學晶格(optical lattice)、squeezing、不同量子系統與量子信息科學的應用等。
</>
<c>
222 U0460
This course discusses the elements of the classical general theory of relativity. It is expected that the students taking this course are already familiar with the language of the special theory of relativity, classical mechanics, and classical electromagnetism. The mathematical prerequisites include linear algebra, differential and integral calculus, vector calculus, and partial differential equations. In addition, do anticipate some messy calculations along the way.
Contents:
(Not necessarily to be strictly followed.)
1.Review of special relativity:
-A fun tour
-The Lorentz transformation
-Thomas precession as a manifestation of length contraction
-Spacetime diagram and 4-vectors
-The metric
-Geometrization of the law of conservation of energy-momentum
-Symmetry can be a severe constraint put in by hand
-Conservation law is a local thing
2.Uniformly accelerated observer, and his neighbors:
-Uniform acceleration is meaningful only to oneself
-Neighbor remaining close downstairs is not experiencing the same acceleration
-An event horizon and particle trajectories
-Nothing strange happens when falling into the event horizon
-The equivalence principle
-The gravitational redshift
3.Curvature:
-Curvature of a spatial curve
-Curvature of a curve lying on a surface
-Detecting the curvature without leaving the surface
-Concept of “connection”
-Parallel transport
-Foucault’s pendulum as a manifestation of parallel transport
-Thomas precession as a manifestation of parallel transport
-An aside on dual space, tensors, and all that
-Strain tensor, stress tensor, and stress-energy tensor
-The Riemann curvature tensor
-Geodesic deviation
4.Einstein’s field equation:
-From Newton’s law of gravitation to its relativistic generalization
-The weak field approximation and interpretation
-Gravitational waves
-The variational formulation
5.The Schwarzschild solution:
-The metric
-Precession of Mercury about the sun
-Bending of starlight near the sun
-The gravitational redshift, again
-The event horizon
-Nothing strange happens when falling into the event horizon
-Black holes
6.Cosmology:
-The Friedman-Robertson-Walker metric
-The expanding universe
</>
<c>
222 U0620
Particle Physics
This is a course for particle physics. Students taking the course are assumed to know some quantum field theory, in particular Feynman rules. After a brief review of Feynman rules, the Standard Model of strong and electroweak interactions will be introduced. The rest of the course will discuss how the SM describes the strong and electroweak interactions, and various processes which supported and helped to confirm and test the SM. Some ideas beyond the SM will be discussed at the end.
</>
<c>
222 U2070
實驗物理專題或理論物理專題是物理系大學部學生的課程，尤其是針對目前演講和討論課所忽略的具體專業與獨立的研究能力所設計，而不是侷限在被動的接受知識與解題能力而已。希望能藉由老師所給予的研究專題，訓練其主動分析問題與解決問題的能力，並參與研究群的討論互動，累積基本研究經驗和認識研究文化，作為未來進一步進入高深研究的基礎能力。指導老師將針對其研究主題特性，設計適當的訓練方式和評量辦法，修課者必須在期末提出口頭報告和書面研究論文。
</>
