303 47600
This course will inherit from Labor Economics (I) to cover further labor market issues from the microeconomics perspective. The focus will be both theoretical derivations and empirical applications. Topics covered will include labor supply, labor demand, labor market, human capital, immigration, gender, unions, and unemployment. The tools covered in the course are directed at undergraduate students conducting research not only in the field of labor economics, but other realms such as public, health, and family economics.
