322 M4040
外交決策分析專題研究為政治研究所國際關係組之選修課程。每星期三下午三時三十分至五時二十分上課。
本課程主要在提供同學未來從事外交決策研究或實際參與外交決策工作之知識領域基礎，並且透過理論與實際的結合，使同學能對外交決策過程建構出清楚的概念。
　　課程將首先介紹外交決策理論，內容涵蓋了當代著名決策理論家的觀點。然後再探討理性、官僚與組織決策模式的內涵與限制。課程中也將討論社會心理決策模式及總統決策模式，以便更深入地探究決策的個人因素。除了常態決策分析外，也將探討危機時的決策型態，以及危機對決策品質升降的影響。課程中也將探究個人決策與聯合集體決策間的不同，並尋找國內政治、國會、利益團體、政治文化、民意、大眾傳播及智庫與外交決策的關係，同時引用實例來深入剖析外交決策的形成過程。
</>
<c>
322 M4050
This is an advanced research seminar on public international law. In the past two centuries, though legal positivism (thus lawyers and conventional legal scholars) dominate the development of international law, both students of new legal realism and political science has begun to rediscover various “political” functions of international law in the past decade. Just to name a few, why and how international law influences states and individual behaviors regardless of lacking of coercive mechanism; why and how conventional functions of sovereignty transforms in the post-World War II era; how to understand the international law in action as opposed to international law in theory. In sum, the fundamental “political” question of international law is why nation complies with international law. Such “political” revival of the research of international law conducted by both international legal and political science scholars suggests a new demand for international law: a coherent international law research methodology from social science perspectives both theoretically and empirically. In hence, we will spend about half of the semester to look into this new international law methodological trend in this seminar, in addition to some of the conventional international law subjects.
In consistent with the aforementioned course interests, this seminar is organized in two parts. The first part of the course provides a general theoretical/ methodological introduction to international law. In response to the aforementioned new demand for re-understanding the international law, this part will put emphasis on cultivating each participant’s ability of asking, answering, and interpreting the role or function of international law, as understood from various methodological and theoretical perspectives. In specific, policy-oriented, rational-choice, transnational legal process, and feminists approaches to international law will be explored. The second part of the course offers three selected specialized areas of international law: economic law, human rights law and the law of the sea.
</>
