330 M1710
人口高齡化是目前世界各國所面臨的共同課題，在我國也不例外。我國的老年人口比率雖比其他福利先進國家為低，但高齡化的速度卻比其他國家為快。在人口高齡化之趨勢下，老年相關給付已成西方福利先進國家最大的社會福利支出項目，而年金與老人照顧體系的改革也是近年來西方國家社會福利發展的最重要課題之一。我國國民年金保險、勞工保險年金制度、勞工退休金新制都已開辦，長期照護保險與公教人員保險老年給付的年金制度也在積極規劃，我國的老年社會政策已邁入一個新的時代，有許多相關的議題，值得深入地探究。本課程主要探討的焦點在人口老化的趨勢與影響、退休與老年經濟保障、老人與照顧議題、以及高齡社會政策的性別與代間議題等
</>
<c>
330 M2100
社會工作的專業化歷程帶來了專業分工，但不可否認的也帶來斷裂與切割。於是作個案的人專注於個案的發包與問題解決，而忘了案主是生存在共同的社會文化情境中；帶團體的人，只考慮眼前的團體目標與活動方案，而忘了改變歷程是牽一髮而動全局的；機構化的結果是讓社會工作者出讓了社區工作的半壁江山而不自知。本課視社會工作的實施為一整體的系統，以綜融的角度來看待社會工作的三大方法之一：團體工作。
團體工作是社會工作的重要介入方式，影響團體成員，但也影響著團體領導者的行為，本課程的目的在於以概念重新建構、反思、經驗學習、討論分享及團體動力實做的方式，讓學習者能更深入探索自己在團體中的行為，以及了解團體的現場究竟發生什麼，整合個人內在覺察與外在互動干預，進而催化團體的過程。
</>
<c>
330 M3660
優勢觀點為社會工作重要實務理論架構之一，運用正向心理學觀點，「持續」建構案主的長處及優勢，促成案主有正向的成長及改變，廣泛運用在當代心理衛生領域。
「正念認知療法」（MBCT Mindfulness Based Cognitive Therapy）是以西方主流心理治療為基礎的禪修療癒法，實踐理念是：全心全意真實的去覺察、去專注、去留意、去體驗當下的每一種感受，以能享受生活並且讓生命發揮到淋漓盡致。這個療法是以形式簡單的「正念冥想」為中心，促進案主的自我效能，每天只需花幾分鐘時間就能享受到它所帶來的益處。臨床結果證實，「正念認知療法」與一般抗抑鬱藥物一樣有效。目前在歐美應用於身心靈療癒、教育、醫護與企業人資，成效卓越，MBCT也成為融合西方主流心理治療與東方禪修的身心療癒法新典範．優勢觀點與正念療癒方法有別於其他學派(如:問題解決、任務取向、行為認知)，社會工作者並不強調以問題或是負向弱勢觀點來面對案主，優勢觀點相信，當人們的正向能力受到支持後他們就會藉由這些正向能力去採取行動，改善自己的生活！正念認知療法則是結合臨床心理與東方禪修的精神，幫助我們打破「不幸福—壓力大—焦慮—精神疲憊」的惡性循環，有效提升真正的生活樂趣，就像內心存在幸福感，滲入所做的每一件事情，幫助個案能領悟生活帶來的逆境打擊，並能生出新的洞察與面對的勇氣。
</>
<c>
330 M4000
Overview
As identity movements spread and globalization impacts everyone’s everyday life, the concept of cultural diversity “takes account of its dynamic nature and the challenges of identity associated with the permanence of cultural change” (United Nations Educational Scientific and Cultural Organization, 2009). Social workers nowadays are obliged to understand and properly respond to the subtle differences across groups of gender, sexuality, age, ethnicity or/and race, area, and social class and the influence on the people. Based on the core value of social justice, issues related to human rights and oppression are also of concern.
This course aims to prepare cultural competence of students in terms of cultural awareness, knowledge acquisition, and skill development. The sessions start with relevant theoretical frameworks, looks into pressing issues of oppressed populations, and ends by reviewing the development of practice, research and social service system. To enrich students’ cross-culture exposure and sharpen sensitivity toward distinct cultures, international guest speakers are invited to present on a series of selective issues in the context of their society. The interactive guest speeches can include a pre-recorded lecture, discussion board on the CEIBA system, and/or live discussion through internet connection in class. For each topic of the guest speech, students work in groups to present a similar or related issue in Taiwan or other societies. Thus, dialogue between societies and among the course participants would occur and deepen the learning experience.
Contents
Part 1. Introduction
(2/26) Course introduction
(3/5) Defining cultural diversity
(3/12) Cultural competence in social work
(3/19) Cultural humility in service learning/ Elisa Martin, Ph.D., Visiting Professor at Siena College, USA
Part 2. Theoretical pieces
(3/26) Social justice and human rights
(4/2) Anti-oppression perspective
(4/16) Postmodern paradigm
Part 3. Selective issues around the world/ Guest speaker
(4/23) Disparity and disproportionality of ethnicities in American children welfare/ Catherine K. Lawrence, Ph.D., Assistant Professor at SUNY Albany; Sharon Kollar, LMSW, LINKD Implementation Coordinator and Adjunct Instructor atNational Child Welfare Workforce Institute; Mary McCarthy, Ph.D., LMSW, Director of Social Work Education Consortium, USA
(4/30) New marriage immigrant and the family in Taiwan/ The instructor
(5/7) New marriage immigrant and the family in Taiwan/ Student presentation
(5/14) Inner immigration from rural to urban areas in China/ Lei Wu, Ph.D., Lecturer at Renmin University of Chin
(5/21) Modern slavery and human trafficking/ Julina Svistova, MSW, SUNY Albany, USA
(5/28) Disaster social work/ Patricia Weldon, Ph.D., Assistant Professor at Marywood University, USA
(6/4) Meaning of life for older adults/ Paul Urbanski, Ph.D., Assistant Professor at Monmouth University, USA
Part 4. Development in practice and research
(6/11) Cultural competent research: Measurement and methodology
(6/18) Cultural competent practice: Skills and techniques; Course wrap-up
(6/25) Final paper due
</>
