426 M4400
This course is designed for Nurse Practitioner students to build up their knowledge and skills in becoming a nurse practitioner capable of diagnosing and managing common health problems in the acute care settings.  Students are required to demonstrate integration, synthesis and application of assessment, diagnosis, and management of patients with complex acute and chronic health conditions.   The main focus of the course is to developing critical thinking processes that required for development of differential diagnosis and management of common health problems.  Collaborative partnerships with patient, family and other health care disciplines are emphasized. This course is required for Nurse Practitioner students in the first year of study with two credit hours.
</>
<c>
426 M4440
This practicum in an acute care environment provides students with direct experience on development of a systematic methodology of identifying patients' needs for health care. The focus of the practicum is on assessment, on risk
isk development and on the subsequent management of selected health problems for a caseload of hospitalized patients. Critical thinking, clinical reasoning and problem solving are emphasized. Practice and mastery of these skills will occur in preceptor clinical settings and will reflect progressive competency of students. Working directly with experienced Nurse Practitioner preceptor will allow for role transition into the 2nd year of specialization. Clinical conferences will focus on cases presented by the students as well as specific topics that relate to management of common health problems in acute care settings. Required for all Nurse Practitioner students in the first year of specialization with nine clinical hours per week (3 credit hours).
</>
