631 M3310
Recent technological advances have enabled the deployment of low-cost, low-power, and multifunctional sensor devices. These devices are autonomous sensor nodes with integrated sensing, processing, and wireless communication capabilities, and then can form the wireless sensor networks (WSNs). This source consists of 15 issues related to WSNs reseach area. Detailed descriptions for various scenarios where WSNs may be applied, and various application-layer tools for enabling such applications will be introduced in the course. The presented applications of WSNs include habit monitoring, biomedical sensor engineering, monitoring environments, water and waste management, and military applications. Also, this course will introduce the required technical issues associated with specific sensor devices, power management, signal processing and computation, operation system, topology construction, broadcasting, data aggregation, etc.
</>
