<c>
725 U3360
To compete in the emerging knowledge-centric economy, many organizations around the world have undertaken various initiatives to manage their most important yet volatile asset—knowledge. Knowledge management (KM) refers to a systematic and organizational process for acquiring/creating, organizing, sharing, transferring, using/applying, and updating both tacit and explicit knowledge to enhance the organizational performance, improve organizational adaptability, increase values of existing products and services, and/or create new knowledge-intensive products, processes and services. While KM was developed first in industries and business functions that are basically selling knowledge—professional services, pharmaceuticals, research and development functions—it is quickly becoming prevalent in other industries, including manufacturing, financial services, and government organizations. It can be expected that most of industries will view themselves as knowledge-intensive and will develop or adopt some KM initiatives in their business units and functions.
The purpose of this course is to provide a comprehensive overview on the emergent practices in KM. Specifically, in this course, we will explain the concepts, theories, and technologies that establish the foundation for KM, processes and strategies for developing and deploying KM initiatives, and organizational, managerial, and behavioral perspectives concerning various KM activities.
</>
<c>
725 U3370
UNDER THE INFLUENCES OF GLOBALIZATION AND DIGITALIZATION, E-BUSINESS IS THE MOST IMPORTANT TOPIC THAT ALL THE COMPANIES ARE LEARNING AND CONSTRUCTING. ACCORDING TO THE MARKETING RESEARCH RESULT OF THE FORRESTER RESEARCH, THE VALUE OF B2B ECONOMICS GROWS TO 1.3 HUNDRED MILLIONS OF US DOLLARS IN 2003 AND HAS BECAME THE MOST VALUABLE IT AND WEB APPLICATION. THIS CLASS IS DESIGNED TO INTRODUCE STUDENTS TO THE IMPORTANT TOPICS IN E-BUSINESS. THE COURSE IS DIVIDED INTO TWO SESSIONS: EB/EC AND MRP/ERP. IN THE FIRST HALF SESSION OF THE CLASS, IMPORTANT TOPICS SUCH AS EB/EC STRATEGY, E-MARKETING, CRM, ETC WILL BE INTRODUCED AND THOROUGHLY DISCUSSED. IN THE SECOND HALF SESSION OF THE CLASS, THE COURSE WILL INCLUDE THE INTRODUCTION AND CLASSIFICATION OF THE PRODUCTION AND MANUFACTURING INDUSTRIES, THE OVERVIEW OF MANUFACTURING RESOURCE PLANNING, DEMAND MANAGEMENT, BILL OF MATERIAL, SHOP FLOOR CONTROL, AND IT TECHNOLOGY USED IN PRODUCTION INDUSTRY.
</>
<c>
725 U3450
過去幾十年來資訊科技在人類文明與社會經濟的進程中扮演了關鍵的角色，隨著網際網路的普及以及行動聯網趨勢崛起，我們的日常生活與資訊科技漸漸變得密不可分。許多從中衍生而來的相關應用，如社群網絡、搜尋引擎、電子商務與物聯網等等，更是對我們的生活造成的莫大的影響與改變。
以往，建置一個應用系統往往需要仰賴複雜的資訊科技 ( 如 Google 的搜尋引擎、Big Data 數據分析 )，技術的掌握也因此成為核心競爭優勢。然而，隨著資通訊基礎建設的普及、技術的成熟與開發工具的完備，技術在許多成功的案例裡已經不再是一個關鍵的角色，取而代之的是應用與服務的創新性。例如，YouTube 的成功在於它創新的“視訊分享”服務模式，而不是它的多媒體串流技術 ( 這項技術在YouTube創立時已經相當成熟 )。 Facebook 令人無法自拔的關鍵不是因為它的系統比其他社交網路服務先進，而是因為它提供了創新的互動模式，讓使用者透過它的服務將真實的生活能夠幾乎原封不動地轉移到線上，一種全新的體驗。除此之外，由於 iPhone 的出現獲得空前的成功，挾帶著使用者經驗風潮興起，許多大企業與新創公司也紛紛將使用者經驗（ User Experience ）的設計理念加入的產品開發的過程之中，從用戶的需求與體驗出發，令產品更能夠符合使用者的期待。
本課程希望透過多個案例，介紹各種創新的資訊科技應用與服務，並激發學生思考新的可能，甚至進一步執行創業計劃，最終成為一名成功的創業家。課程的內容將透過幾個創新基本思考原則來傳授。
另外，如果將創新象徵為創業者的手中的矛，賦予商業上的競爭優勢，那麼專利便能比喻成保護創業者的盾，為新創事業構築一道堅固的防禦體系。因此本課程亦將介紹智慧財產權與專利，並以一些創新性的專利，來說明專利的申請要件，以及如何運用專利強化競爭優勢。
</>
