102 83030
The course introduces ICT-based (Information and Communication Technology) foreign language learning strategies that help students build up their own personal learning framework, a vital element of foreign language learning which allows students to define, manage and self-regulate their learning continuously; thus, equipping them with the core skills of foreign language learning (i.e. awareness of language learning structures, linguistic knowledge, communication skills, proactive attitude).
</>
<c>
102 83030
This course is designed to introduce NTU students to university-level English. We will continue to develop the academic skills we learned last semester, notably reading texts critically and responding to them through research; we will also review other fundamental skills including punctuation, spelling, and mechanics. We will then read and discuss a series of texts introducing and presenting popular literary genres including the romance, horror, detective, adventure (science fiction), and fantasy fictions. Students will have a chance to apply the skills they have learned through ten listening transcriptions, two midterms and, near the end of this course, through a group presentation. Students are expected to attend regularly, to read with care and curiosity, and to bring an open mind to course assignments and class discussions. We will engage with issues of popular literature by examining how popular literary genres gain meaning in contemporary culture and how they are an integral and important aspect of our lives.
</>
<c>
102 83030
This course is aimed at helping students to become successful users of English. Students are presented with content that is interesting and thought provoking and from which language skill development exercises naturally flow. Students are trained in various language skills through exposure to the language in situations that allow them to make a personal connection with the topics. In addition, students are induced to acquire language in a natural way through watching a fun TV series.
</>
<c>
102 83030
This course is aimed at helping students to become successful users of English.  Apart from listening and writing practice, we will have close reading of literature. Denotations and connotations as well as issues such as gender, race, and class raised by the texts will be discussed in class for an in-depth understanding of both the language and the content.  After each reading, questions will be given in class for group discussion and oral presentation.  For this semester, we will study a short story by Katherine Ann Porter, essays by Daniel Altman, William Tsutsui, and Carlos Saldanha, plays by August Strindberg and Sophocles, and, if we have time, poems by Shakespeare and Emily Dickinson.  Students are also required to give drama presentation in English at the end of the semester.
</>
<c>
102 83030
As (Freshman) English I
&
II may be the last required course for many students on their way of learning English, this class is designed with the main purpose of cultivating students` future capability of independent study and use of the language, particularly with respect to reading. Thus various types of reading materials-such as the latest news reports, argumentative essays (on all kinds of subjects) and literary works (mostly short stories)-will be covered in the class, always with emphasis on developing essential reading skills. As all the reading materials will be in handout form, the class is devoid of a standard textbook; however, every student will need to possess a dictionary equipped with English definitions and complete-sentence examples.
</>
<c>
102 83030
This English course focuses on reading and discussion; its main objective consists in cultivating students’ sophisticated and critical thinking on cultural topics. This course will be run mostly in all-English way, with the aim to engage students in intellectual, critical discussions in English. Therefore, students who expect and need concentrated training on practical skills, such as real-life conversation, are not recommended to take this course. Mandarin will be used when complex concepts need to be clarified. The reading material pertains to various genres, including poetry, fiction, critical essay, and film. The issues to be explored include (1) love, (2) virtual relationship, (3) domination and the Holocaust, and (4) religion. Students are required to commit themselves to (1) close reading to acquire a deeper understanding of the text, and (2) continuous collaboration through teamwork and group discussion in order to test and substantiate their grasp of the issue concerned. In general, the objectives to be achieved include the following: (1) to introduce cultural topics which preoccupy the present intellectual world; (2) to enhance students’ critical and sophisticated thinking; (3) to enhance students’ ability to discuss and write on complex, intellectual issues in English. The requirements for students include: (1) interest in thinking; (2) class attendance and active participation; (3) class activities and exercises; (4) close teamwork.
</>
<c>
102 83030
This course is designed to enhance mainly your reading proficiency through an extensive exposure to a diverse range of quality writings in English. We shall be reading from a selection of literature and the media writings. In terms of literature, we shall be studying short stories, poems, essays and dramas. As for the media, we shall be focusing on both the print and cyber media, including mainstream press such as Time, New York Times, and alternative, critical media such as Z-net and The Nation. To facilitate your listening capacity, the course will be conducted in both English and Mandarin, depending on your classroom response. To help you to express yourself in English, I shall encourage you to speak up in class, and participate in our forums and debates in English.
There will be a mid-term (30%), a final (40%) and various off-the-cuff quizzes and on-the-spot assignments (10%) in class. A group project (20%) would involve either a drama presentation (acting or reading) or a collaborative academic review (on an approved subject of your choice). Required course material will be a reader (or handouts in class) and a play which can be purchased in the bookstore.
The course material, syllabus, and grade quotient are all subject
to change pending on further notice.
Course material
Short stories by Hemingway, Fitzgerald, Malamud, Carver, Oates, Gish Jen. (handouts or on reserve)
Poems by Shakepeare, Blake, Keats, Shelley, Byron, Yeats, Thomas,
Housman, Whitman, Dickinson, Frost, Lowell, Bishop, Plath, Ginsberg, Hughes, Aneglou, Merwin, Strand. (all handouts)
Essays by Montaigne (translation), Emerson, Woolf, Rachel Carson,
C. P. Snow, Steven Weinberg, Stephen Jay Gould, Wang Hao.
(handouts or on reserve)
Plays: Edward Albee's The Zoo Story (for law school students), or Friedrich Durrenmatt's The Physicists (for science, EE, medical and agriculture students).
Some of the assigned readings will be available in the reserve area at the main library
Reports and reviews from Time, N
