<c>
102 83320
This integrated language course aims to enhance students’ English proficiency at the high-intermediate level. The course is also intended to develop in the students an interest in learning English and a more thorough understanding of the English and American culture, as well as to improve students’ critical thinking and presentation skills. Students will be introduced to social and cultural topics that are relevant to college life, including entertainment, education, pop culture, technology, career, etc.
The course will balance lectures with various classroom activities involving four skills (reading, listening, writing, and speaking). These learning activities include group discussion and oral presentation, Q and A, film viewing and critique, performance, and language games. Frequent writing exercises are designed to relate the course material to the students’ own life experience.
In addition to sharpening the students’ English skills, after taking this course, students are expected to become critical readers and thinkers, clear communicators in multiple contexts, and active analysts of contemporary cultures.
This class will be taught mainly in English. You are encouraged to interact with your instructor and TA in English.
(Please be advised that the syllabus is subject to change. The final version will be distributed in the first class.)
</>
<c>
102 83320
The 18-week English course emphasises conversation skills, and students are given opportunities to use English during in-class discussion sessions. The training of English reading is combined with oral practice. Students may think the reading texts are relatively easier than what they have read in high school, in terms of sentence patterns and vocabulary use. However, the material for the reading text we use is always chosen for its clarity and because it can arouse student opinions. The reading comprehension is checked via speaking. The writing part is done through doing three writing assignments throughout the term. There will also be group projects and group work.
</>
<c>
102 83320
待補Welcome back to the second semester of FE. I look forward to another chance to improve our English skills, not just in writing and reading, but also in speaking. Henry has graciously agreed to be our TA again, and I thank him for a job well done. He and I will map out a plan for this semester and most likely overhaul the required assignments to include not just writing tasks. I will continue to give you handouts in English and lecture on various topics that may pique your curiosity in the first 2 hours and let Henry take over the last hour with his interesting activities. This semester I want you to help choose essays for the lectures. You can suggest topics that you find interesting or even propose certain essays for class. Since you are all liberal arts majors, you may want to pick a poem or two or even a short story. And if you are not a big fan of lectures, we can always switch to a more interactive format for our meetings. Although you cannot count on me to act, Henry is a born actor. The aim of this course remains unchanged. Our goal is to help you develop authentic English skills, skills that may make a difference in your career down the road. I am very happy with your performance last semester and want you to have a better experience this time. If there is anything I really want to change, I want more participation from you. I will make sure that I give all of you equal attention, and that each of you will have a chance to answer my questions in class. Again, I emphasize regular attendance not just because it is mandated by university law, but more because the classroom is where education takes place, and if you are absent, you forfeit your chances. However, if you can maintain a solid attendance record, you can pretty much expect the same generous grades from me, based on the same formula we used last semester. Remember, after this semester, you will not be entitled to virtually free, high-quality English lessons, and you will have to pay people to revise your essays and writing drafts. As always, your feedback and comments are most welcome. You can reach me by sending me an email (drleung@ntu.edu.tw) or via Henry. I wish all of you a pleasant and productive semester.
</>
<c>
102 83320
This is an integrated language course tailored for non-English majors. It is designed to help students at high intermediate level to make full use of their current English proficiency and to further upgrade it to advanced level. It demands a lot of hard work and challenges the students to develop higher cognitive skills. It also aims at developing in the students an interest in learning English, further understanding of the English culture, critical thinking, and creativity.
While Internet is the key source of listening and reading materials, some language course books will also be consulted. Every 3-hour session will start with exercises in vocabulary and listening, continue with class discussion of assigned reading materials, and end with task-based speaking activities. A quiz on vocabulary and the reading materials will be held every month and an oral examination on the task-based speaking activities will take place at the end of the semester. The students will also need to submit three pieces of writing (Submission dates: weeks 7, 11, and 15)
</>
<c>
102 83320
We will spend about 2/3 of the class reading various texts (mainly news articles, but a few essays and literary works as well), and the remaining 1/3 practicing listening. In order to enlarge your vocabulary and to take care of the diverse interests of the students, we will read on a variety of subjects: the arts, natural science, technology, social issues, economy, etc. Photocopies of the reading materials will be handed out in class.
</>
