<c>
102 83320
The focus of this 4-skill integrated course is to reinforce and enhance the English proficiency of students. Throughout the course, students will be given ample opportunities to practice their listening skills through teacher's presentations and interactions with peers. Students will be exposed to reading materials of different genres to develop their interests in English reading and build up their reading fluency. In this course, students will also have the chance to enjoy the pleasure of reading by reading an English novel. It is with hope that students will continue their reading habit after the course is over.
This course is also designed to increase students' confidence to converse comfortably using the English language in everyday context. Much class time will be devoted to student-led activities allowing students to use what they have learned during in-class listening activities to discuss a variety of topics at a sophisticated level. Students will also continue to learn to develop well-structured written messages and coherent and cohesive essays.
</>
<c>
102 83320
This course is designed to introduce NTU students to university-level English. We will continue to develop the academic skills we learned last semester, notably reading texts critically and responding to them through research; we will also review other fundamental skills including punctuation, spelling, and mechanics. We will then read and discuss a series of texts introducing and presenting popular literary genres including the romance, horror, detective, adventure (science fiction), and fantasy fictions. Students will have a chance to apply the skills they have learned through ten listening transcriptions, two midterms and, near the end of this course, through a group presentation. Students are expected to attend regularly, to read with care and curiosity, and to bring an open mind to course assignments and class discussions. We will engage with issues of popular literature by examining how popular literary genres gain meaning in contemporary culture and how they are an integral and important aspect of our lives.
</>
<c>
102 83320
In this class, students will be studying literature from different cultures around the world. The texts for them to be read include short stories, novels, poems, and plays. This literary study will be able to broaden their perspective of the world and deepen their understanding of the universal human condition. They will be asked to write some reports and participate actively in class discussion. They will also be initiated into the domains of art and music which now and then draw inspiration from literature.
</>
<c>
102 83320
This class will provide a general introduction of academic research.  The ultimate goal of this class is to increase communication ability—both in speaking and writing, but the specific focus (with regard to coursework) will be on formal style and research writing.  Students will be expected to actively participate in their own learning process, to find ideas of interest, to develop clear, well-supported arguments, and to both search for and present (in-writing) facts and data to support their position.  Students will also be expected to share and discuss their ideas with their classmates, and work closely with their group members in the peer-review process.
Although the class goals are universal to any language, this class will be conducted entirely in English, and students will be given ample opportunity each week to practice and improve their speaking and listening skills.  The majority of class time will be devoted to student presentations and idea sharing.  Homework will consist mostly of reading academic articles, with short review activities held at the beginning of the next class.  Readings have been specifically chosen by your instructor to encourage class discussion and lead into writing assignments. There will be no exams in this course.
</>
<c>
102 83320
The 18-week English course emphasises conversation skills, and students are given opportunities to use English during in-class discussion sessions. The training of English reading is combined with oral practice. Students may think the reading texts are relatively easier than what they have read in high school, in terms of sentence patterns and vocabulary use. However, the material for the reading text we use is always chosen for its clarity and because it can arouse student opinions. The reading comprehension is checked via speaking. The writing part is done through doing three writing assignments throughout the term. There will also be group projects and group work.
</>
<c>
102 83320
課程說明
（一） 本課程以寫作與閱讀的訓練為主，聽、說訓練為輔，內容則結合英語訓練、文學作品與電影欣賞，以及社會議題的認識及討論。
（二） 本課程教材內容參見底下的「課程進度表」。
（三） 選修本課者必須 1）準時到教室上課；2）充分準備並參與課堂討論；3）準時交作業（句法練習作業及作文）；4）參加考試（小考及期末考）。
</>
<c>
102 83320
The primary purpose of this course is to improve students’ proficiency of English through reading, writing, listening, and oral practices. In order to prepare students for further academic pursuits or advanced English studies, various types of reading materials will be included in the course, especially articles related to major cultural practices and issues, such as race, gender, class, and pop culture. In other words, this is a course which not only purports to improve students’ English capability but also aims to achieve that objective by cultivating their sensitivity to important cultural issues. Students of the class will be divided into groups and discuss questions developed from the reading material in English, and after the discussion, one member of the group has to present the conclusion to the whole class in English. As for listening practices, each week one or two latest video clips from CNN will be broadcasted in class to which students will have to answer questions prepared by the instructor. In addition, 3 short summaries of the reading materials are required.
</>
<c>
102 83320
This class will provide preparation and practice for the use of English-language skills in both academic and real-life contexts and situations.  The ultimate goal of this class is to increase communication ability—both in speaking and writing, but to reach that goal, students must WANT to improve their English and be motivated in pursuing every opportunity for learning.  Students will be expected to speak informally to each-other and to their teacher (formal presentations—to the entire class, as well as in smaller groups—are also required).  Also, your instructor will only speak English to you, so it is important that you understand what he is saying, and that you ask questions when you do not understand.
Reading is also a vital part of language learning, and you will be asked to read articles and build your vocabulary in-class and for homework every week.  The class readings have been specifically chosen by your instructor to encourage class discussion and lead into writing assignments. Understanding formal style and producing academic writing will also be major focus points of this class.
</>
<c>
102 83320
Course Description
This integrated English course aims to enhance students’ English proficiency and help students foster an interest in learning English and a rounded understanding of English and American cultures. Critical thinking is also of the essence in this course, and students are expected to become critical readers and thinkers.
Each week’s section is divided into three parts––listening, reading, and group discussion.
*The syllabus might be updated.
</>
<c>
102 83320
Freshman English
Time: Wednesday 9:10-12:00 am
Classroom: 外教中心 201
Instructor: Prof. Chin-jung Chiu
Office Phone: 3366-3154
Office Hours: by appointment for time
Email: jung @ntu.edu.tw
TA: 陳  奕    b00102017@ntu.edu.tw
Mobile Phone: 0917167121
Course Description
Aimed at enhancing the four skills, this course will improve students’ ability to think, speak, express and debate in English language. (1) Reading: Selections are from literary works including poetry, essays, drama, and, above all, selected scenes from Shakespeare’s plays. (2) Writing: Students are required to write two short compositions and one ppt script (for in-class presentation on an assigned topic). (3) Listening will cover a wide range of topics such as speed dating, secrets of the sexes, behavior training, national stereotypes and selections from BBC’s “Learning English” website. "Clear Pronunciation 2" will be used in class for drills. (4) Speaking aims at daily life conversation and topic-oriented presentation for college-level work. The three-hour course is in general divided into three sections: student presentation, in-class discussion, and guided reading for literary works. Organized around lectures and student discussions/presentations, the course is designed to be collaborative throughout.
Reminders for Students
1. If you miss three class sessions, you shall not expect to receive any favour when you fail the course.
2. Any late submission of compositions after the due date will incur late penalities: receiving a deduction of 2 points per calendar day. 3. All assignments have to be word-processed, double-spaced, and submitted in class or online  according to Professor Chiu’s instruction. Note that Ceiba shuts off “uploading assignments” from 21-24 each day, so you must submit your composition before 9:00 pm.
4. Do not bring a laptop or other electronic device for use in class discussion except for presentation or performance.
評分標準 (Grading Policy)
The final grade will be based on exams, tests, presentations, performances, discussions and class participation (each ranges from 5%-25%), processed by Excel and open to inquiries.
</>
