241 U1300
THIS COURSE FOCUSES ON THE OCEAN’S ROLE IN THE GLOBAL BIOGEOCHEMICAL CYCLING OF ELEMENTS. THE IMPACT OF HUMANS ON THE TRANSPORT OF ELEMENTS WITHIN THESE CYCLES IS GIVING SPECIAL ATTENTION. BASIC OCEAN CHEMISTRY IS FIRST GIVEN AND DISCUSSED. THE CONCEPT OF GLOBAL GEOCHEMICAL CYCLE IS GIVING BASED ON WATER/ROCK INTERACTION. NUTRIENTS AND TRACE METALS CYCLING IS DISCUSSED BASED ON THE PERSPECTIVE OF REDOX REACTIONS, WITH SPECIAL EMPHASIS OF BIOLOGICALLY MEDIATED OXIDATION OF ORGANIC MATTER. STEADY STATE MODELS ARE USED TO EXPLAIN THEIR GLOBAL OCEANIC DISTRIBUTION. SEDIMENT’S ROLE OVER OCEAN CHEMICAL COMPOSITION IS DISCUSSED FROM BOTH EQUILIBRIUM AND KINETIC PERSPECTIVES. MARINE CHEMISTRY OF RADIOACTIVE AND STABLE ISOTOPES ARE ALSO DISCUSSED. THIS COURSE INCLUDES A NUMBER OF BASIC CONCEPTS OF OCEAN CHEMISTRY FOR THE YOUNG MARINE SCIENTISTS. NO PREREQUISITE IS REQUIRED.
